Critical x Meta

Author

Ambra Perugini

Published

October 13, 2025

What and Why?

I am trying to apply critical effect size values to meta-analysis and mini-meta. The goal is to demonstrate the utility of critical effect size values in practice and also evaluate with some examples what is going on in social psychology.

What is an effect size?

The smallest detectable effect that can reach statistical significance given a specific sample size, alpha level, and test statistic.

Basically converting the critical t into a critical Cohenâs d for example.

Meta-analysis

We want to have different scenarios:

  • one with small sample size for individual studies

  • one with large sample size for individual studies

Talamini et al. (2017)

We have decided to use the meta-analysis by Talamini et al. (2017) as an example of small samples.

It has:

  • long term memory,

  • short term memory

  • working memory

We will compute critical values both for one tailed and two tailed t-test, assuming alpha at the .05 threshold and plot the two tailed t-test for now.

Long Term Memory

Letâs plot critical values (for a two tailed test) next to the actual effect sizes.

We compared the estimated meta-analytic effect size to the critical values of individual studies. In 0% of cases, the critical value was lower than the meta-analytic effect size, indicating that these studies would have been able to detect a statistically significant effect of that magnitude. When comparing the critical values to the bias corrected meta-analytic effect size the percentage was still 0%, as it couldnât go any lower.

Short Term Memory

Letâs plot critical values (for a two tailed test) next to the actual effect sizes. We compared the estimated meta-analytic effect size to the critical values of individual studies. In 30% of cases, the critical value was lower than the meta-analytic effect size, indicating that these studies would have been able to detect a statistically significant effect of that magnitude. When comparing the critical values to the bias corrected meta-analytic effect size the percentage lowered to 0%.

In 15.79% of cases, the critical value was lower than the meta-analytic effect size, indicating that these studies would have been able to detect a statistically significant effect of that magnitude.

Shannon et al. (2022)

Chu et al. (2023) is an example of really large samples and a non-significant result, unfortunately not useful to support our thesis. So I decided to focus on Chu et al. (2023) which has big samples and a meta-analytic significant effect and studies correlations of depression and social media use in young adolescents.

This case is a good example of all studies having critical effect size values lower than the meta-analytic effect (100%) meaning that even the individual studies where suited to find a significant effect if there was one as in this case, it is also probably due to the nature of the research field of online data collection that makes it easier to have bigger samples.

Mini meta

We also want to use a mini meta, and for this purpose we are using as a toy example the one by Tuk et al. (2015). They were investigating, in a total of 18 studies, self-control tasks (inhibitory spillover). The amount of times in which the single study had a critical value smaller than the meta-analytic effect was 0%, meaning that each single study didnât reach even 50% power for the meta-analytic effect.

Who cited the metas did implement knowledge into sample size?

Talamini et al. (2017)

For now I have downloaded 133 out of 215 citations.

Min (2025) -> 400 (200 x group, independent t-tests) no power analysis or sample size formalized justification

Jakubowski et al. (2025) -> unrelated research question

Cara (2024) -> 70 (35 x group) ANCOVA, no power analysis or sample size justification

Price-Mohr & Price (2021) -> 15 intervention and 17 control ANCOVA, found significant effect of intervention 4h music training, no power or sample size justification

Byczynski et al. (2022) -> 16 children (8 x group), EEG study, no sample size justification, independent sample t-test

Gray et al. (2025) -> 75 and 55 x group, no planned sample size because they had access to a court study, crazy amount of variables including cognitive ones

Jakubowski et al. (2025) -> 304 subjects, unrelated measures, no justification
